Like I saved his life.
"Thank you, man!"

502
00:18:24,270 --> 00:18:25,688
[hyperventilates]

503
00:18:26,231 --> 00:18:27,982
So the next morning, I wake up,

504
00:18:28,108 --> 00:18:30,693
and my wife calls me
from the theater

505
00:18:31,027 --> 00:18:33,279
and <i>says,</i>
"Did you invite some guy

506
00:18:33,404 --> 00:18:35,698
to come and take my class
this morning?"

507
00:18:35,824 --> 00:18:36,866
I said, "Oh!"

508
00:18:38,118 --> 00:18:39,702
"Yeah, I did, but I, I, I,"

509
00:18:41,162 --> 00:18:43,748
"I didn't think
he would ever show up,"

510
00:18:43,873 --> 00:18:45,154
and she says, "Well, he's here,"

511
00:18:45,208 --> 00:18:46,459
"and he brought
a case of beer."

512
00:18:46,584 --> 00:18:47,627
[laughs]

513
00:18:49,129 --> 00:18:50,171
- Hi there.

514
00:18:50,463 --> 00:18:53,383
Officer Fred McGuire,
local one-niner-niner.

515
00:18:53,508 --> 00:18:55,969
- Kind of jaw-dropping at times
to watch Chris work,

516
00:18:56,094 --> 00:18:58,346
even on a local little stage
like the Ark.

517
00:18:58,471 --> 00:19:01,808
The power of his talent was,
even in a raw state,

518
00:19:03,434 --> 00:19:04,769
was so undeniable.

519
00:19:05,061 --> 00:19:06,938
-[mumbles as the Godfather]

520
00:19:07,063 --> 00:19:09,357
- He just had such presence
and charisma.

521
00:19:09,482 --> 00:19:13,903
- Chris had this amazing talent,
this perfect storm of comedy.

522
00:19:14,154 --> 00:19:15,321
Boom!
Obvious.

523
00:19:16,322 --> 00:19:18,741
- My love, you ate
the liverwurst!

524
00:19:19,284 --> 00:19:20,326
- I was hungry.

525
00:19:21,286 --> 00:19:24,289
- He found this art form
where you work in an ensemble,

526
00:19:24,414 --> 00:19:26,624
and, you know,
you work off each other,

527
00:19:26,749 --> 00:19:27,959
and there's no denial.

528
00:19:28,084 --> 00:19:30,003
It's all about acceptance.

529
00:19:30,211 --> 00:19:31,796
- I do remember
going every weekend

530
00:19:31,921 --> 00:19:33,047
and laughing my head off.

531
00:19:33,173 --> 00:19:34,632
I mean, I wouldn't miss it.
It was the best.

532
00:19:34,757 --> 00:19:35,958
- The shows were really weird.

533
00:19:36,050 --> 00:19:38,219
The shows were, like, bizarre.

534
00:19:38,386 --> 00:19:40,180
I didn't even get any of them.

535
00:19:40,305 --> 00:19:42,140
Chris would come out
<i>as</i> Elvis, Fat Elvis.

536
00:19:42,265 --> 00:19:45,351
"Well, bless my soul,
what's wrong with me?

537
00:19:45,518 --> 00:19:46,811
I think I shit my pants."

538
00:19:46,936 --> 00:19:48,146
- And then
he'd keel over on stage,

539
00:19:48,271 --> 00:19:49,564
and the lights would go out.

540
00:19:49,689 --> 00:19:50,607
-[imitates curtain falling]

541
00:19:50,732 --> 00:19:52,734
"Okay, what did we just watch?"

542
00:19:59,407 --> 00:20:02,327
- See, the thing about Chris
is his heart,

543
00:20:03,620 --> 00:20:05,455
this really kind, gentle,

544
00:20:05,872 --> 00:20:07,790
childish, innocent heart,

545
00:20:09,959 --> 00:20:12,462
which, I say,
was the perfect storm,

546
00:20:12,587 --> 00:20:15,256
because
in that kind and gentle heart

547
00:20:17,258 --> 00:20:19,761
was also
a very frightened person.

548
00:20:21,304 --> 00:20:22,722
I was sad to see him go

549
00:20:23,431 --> 00:20:25,642
because I thought
it was too soon.

550
00:20:25,767 --> 00:20:28,853
He was just beginning improv
and coming into a craft,

551
00:20:28,978 --> 00:20:33,399
as opposed to a party guy,
a party trick.

552
00:20:38,238 --> 00:20:41,032
- Chris comes down to Chicago,
and we hook up.

553
00:20:41,157 --> 00:20:43,118
We know Second City's the mecca.
That's the place.

554
00:20:43,201 --> 00:20:44,761
We don't know what to do
or where to go,

555
00:20:44,869 --> 00:20:47,288
but we've gotta
do this together.

556
00:20:48,164 --> 00:20:50,124
We're just pacing
in front of Second City,

557
00:20:50,250 --> 00:20:52,293
and I swear both of us
kind of thought

558
00:20:52,418 --> 00:20:53,878
that on the second
or third floor

559
00:20:54,003 --> 00:20:55,171
of the Second City offices,

560
00:20:55,296 --> 00:20:57,017
somebody was going to look down
and be like,

561
00:20:57,048 --> 00:20:58,967
"Well, then we just need
two more people,"

562
00:20:59,092 --> 00:21:00,343
"or we're not going
to have a show tonight."

563
00:21:00,468 --> 00:21:02,428
"Hey, those two fellows
look pretty funny."

564
00:21:02,553 --> 00:21:03,888
As if you're going
to walk around Wrigley Field

565
00:21:04,013 --> 00:21:05,056
and have, "Hey!"
[creaking]

566
00:21:05,181 --> 00:21:06,808
"Come on in.
Play some ball."

567
00:21:09,435 --> 00:21:10,478
- He called to tell me,

568
00:21:10,603 --> 00:21:12,355
"I got into the classes
at Second City,"

569
00:21:12,480 --> 00:21:14,691
and I was like,
"Wow, that's awesome!"

570
00:21:14,816 --> 00:21:17,151
- He was far more ambitious
than I ever thought.

571
00:21:17,277 --> 00:21:19,529
I didn't know
that he would pursue training

572
00:21:19,654 --> 00:21:21,406
and end up with Del Close,

573
00:21:21,906 --> 00:21:24,284
king shit
of improvisational acting.

574
00:21:24,409 --> 00:21:25,243
- I wanted to really show

575
00:21:25,368 --> 00:21:27,328
that we could create art
by committee.

576
00:21:27,453 --> 00:21:29,372
Nothing that I hear
is going to be simple.

577
00:21:29,497 --> 00:21:31,249
Nothing that you say to me

578
00:21:31,416 --> 00:21:33,376
is going to be accepted
at face value.

579
00:21:33,501 --> 00:21:35,461
It always means something else.

580
00:21:35,586 --> 00:21:37,880
- Del Close
was a fantastic improviser,

581
00:21:38,006 --> 00:21:39,090
great teacher.

582
00:21:39,299 --> 00:21:40,299
He didn't teach comedy,

583
00:21:40,383 --> 00:21:41,904
because I don't think
that's teachable,

584
00:21:41,968 --> 00:21:43,386
but he taught creativity.

585
00:21:43,511 --> 00:21:45,596
Del was the creative Svengali

586
00:21:45,888 --> 00:21:48,391
of Bill Murray,
Belushi, Aykroyd.

587
00:21:50,059 --> 00:21:53,062
- Del was the chief
anarchist artist there.

588
00:21:53,187 --> 00:21:55,773
What he taught all of us
was to be free

589
00:21:56,316 --> 00:21:57,567
and to be unafraid

590
00:21:58,484 --> 00:22:00,987
and to go out and fail
as often as possible,

591
00:22:01,112 --> 00:22:03,197
to try things, to die onstage.

592
00:22:04,532 --> 00:22:05,825
He threw off convention

593
00:22:05,950 --> 00:22:07,391
and kind of blew the lid
off the form

594
00:22:07,410 --> 00:22:09,704
so that we could really
do the freest work,

595
00:22:09,829 --> 00:22:11,748
um, that we were capable of.

596
00:22:12,790 --> 00:22:13,791
- Okay, do it.

597
00:22:18,087 --> 00:22:19,505
And that's the lighting we have?

598
00:22:19,630 --> 00:22:20,673
Okay.

599
00:22:21,257 --> 00:22:22,425
- We realize perfectly well

600
00:22:22,550 --> 00:22:23,951
that all the characters
that we play

601
00:22:23,968 --> 00:22:26,304
are really subsets of ourselves,

602
00:22:27,305 --> 00:22:30,391
they're just ourselves
in slightly different moods,

603
00:22:30,516 --> 00:22:34,187
ourselves carrying
a little more emotional freight.

604
00:22:34,312 --> 00:22:35,897
- Del said, "Mr. Myers,"

605
00:22:36,522 --> 00:22:39,942
"there's somebody who I think
is a kindred spirit"

606
00:22:40,109 --> 00:22:41,444
"that you have to meet."

607
00:22:41,569 --> 00:22:43,321
"You have to meet Farley."

608
00:22:44,530 --> 00:22:45,573
So I met him.

609
00:22:46,115 --> 00:22:47,325
The second I saw him,

610
00:22:47,450 --> 00:22:49,285
I thought he was going
to be a giant star.

611
00:22:49,410 --> 00:22:51,704
- If he had just been
a big, funny guy that fell down,

612
00:22:51,829 --> 00:22:54,374
Del Close certainly never would
have cast him at Second City.

613
00:22:54,499 --> 00:22:55,958
Del Close
would have washed him out

614
00:22:56,084 --> 00:22:57,126
right away.

615
00:22:57,543 --> 00:22:59,384
He had no time for people
that were just funny,

616
00:22:59,462 --> 00:23:02,340
and if someone sold out a scene
for a joke,

617
00:23:02,465 --> 00:23:04,342
Del would sometimes
just throw them offstage.

618
00:23:04,467 --> 00:23:06,427
He's like, "Get the hell
out of here, you turkey."

619
00:23:06,552 --> 00:23:09,889
Dell wanted to work with Chris
because he was funny and honest.

620
00:23:10,014 --> 00:23:11,099
- The smallest,

621
00:23:11,599 --> 00:23:15,686
the teeniest, weeniest
emotional discovery that's real

622
00:23:16,354 --> 00:23:17,354
beats the hell

623
00:23:17,397 --> 00:23:19,982
out of the biggest one
that's phony,

624
00:23:20,358 --> 00:23:21,442
and that's why our audience,
I think,

625
00:23:21,567 --> 00:23:23,069
is so much on our side,

626
00:23:24,278 --> 00:23:25,559
because they want us to succeed.

627
00:23:25,613 --> 00:23:28,324
They have this...
They're cheering us on.

628
00:23:28,449 --> 00:23:31,244
- "To treat the audience
like poets and kings,

629
00:23:31,369 --> 00:23:33,162
and they'll respond in kind."

630
00:23:33,287 --> 00:23:34,455
I've always felt that way,

631
00:23:34,580 --> 00:23:36,958
and I saw it completely embodied
in Chris Farley.

632
00:23:37,083 --> 00:23:38,334
- Del loved Chris,

633
00:23:39,001 --> 00:23:40,128
so it's no surprise to me

634
00:23:40,253 --> 00:23:43,339
that Del plucked him
for the mainstage cast

635
00:23:43,798 --> 00:23:45,133
almost immediately.

636
00:23:45,258 --> 00:23:46,300
- Hello there.

637
00:23:48,302 --> 00:23:49,543
This must be the birthday girl.

638
00:23:49,679 --> 00:23:50,513
- That's right.

639
00:23:50,638 --> 00:23:52,640
- Hi, birthday girl.
Doogie Howser.

640
00:23:52,765 --> 00:23:54,100
[audience laughs]

641
00:23:56,477 --> 00:23:58,229
Well, I guess, then,
little birthday girl,

642
00:23:58,354 --> 00:23:59,689
this one's for you.

643
00:24:00,982 --> 00:24:04,402
[music]

644
00:24:10,575 --> 00:24:13,453
- For Chris, I think
Del was the Lamaze birth coach

645
00:24:13,578 --> 00:24:14,912
that kind of pulled

646
00:24:15,329 --> 00:24:18,666
all of everything
that was inside of Chris out.

647
00:24:19,417 --> 00:24:20,960
- He said the same thing to Chris
that he said to Belushi,

648
00:24:21,085 --> 00:24:24,046
which is "Go out there,
attack the stage like a bull."

649
00:24:24,172 --> 00:24:25,381
"You have that kind of power."

650
00:24:25,506 --> 00:24:27,467
"Just try to kill them
with laughter."

651
00:24:27,592 --> 00:24:28,592
"Just kill them."

652
00:24:28,676 --> 00:24:30,845
- Chris on stage was crazy,
force of nature,

653
00:24:30,970 --> 00:24:32,138
through the roof,

654
00:24:32,263 --> 00:24:37,685
quantitatively, qualitatively
amped up past everybody else.

655
00:24:39,353 --> 00:24:42,482
- His basic impulse
is to make situations funny.

656
00:24:42,607 --> 00:24:44,734
He was taught
"Don't stifle that."

657
00:24:44,859 --> 00:24:45,902
"Expand on it."

658
00:24:47,361 --> 00:24:48,404
He found his identity with that,

659
00:24:48,529 --> 00:24:51,365
because that was
his natural impulse as a kid.

660
00:24:51,491 --> 00:24:53,451
- It was really that feeling
of, like, "I get it."

661
00:24:53,534 --> 00:24:54,702
"I'm only going
to watch that guy"

662
00:24:54,827 --> 00:24:55,995
"if he's onstage,"

663
00:24:56,370 --> 00:24:57,890
"because there's nothing
touching him."

664
00:24:57,914 --> 00:25:00,541
"He is wildly entertaining."

665
00:25:02,293 --> 00:25:03,961
- I improvised
with Chris Farley,

666
00:25:04,086 --> 00:25:05,630
and I was scared to death

667
00:25:05,755 --> 00:25:07,507
because he had already
knocked somebody's tooth out

668
00:25:07,632 --> 00:25:09,592
and gave somebody else a scar

669
00:25:09,717 --> 00:25:11,469
from just being so crazy,

670
00:25:11,594 --> 00:25:13,596
and I'm...
I mean, I have a lot of energy,

671
00:25:13,721 --> 00:25:14,680
but I don't have that energy.

672
00:25:14,805 --> 00:25:15,848
- Jesus...

673
00:25:16,557 --> 00:25:19,769
right before he'd go on stage,
he'd drop his pants,

674
00:25:19,894 --> 00:25:22,730
and just pull them up
at the last second.

675
00:25:23,231 --> 00:25:24,391
So you're standing behind him

676
00:25:24,482 --> 00:25:27,068
because
if you have to go out next...

677
00:25:27,360 --> 00:25:28,611
you get that view.

678
00:25:28,736 --> 00:25:30,988
- It was
a very beer-soaked culture

679
00:25:31,113 --> 00:25:32,657
in the improv world, you know.

680
00:25:32,782 --> 00:25:34,283
We all drank too much.

681
00:25:34,492 --> 00:25:37,620
Parties usually involved
way too much beer drinking.

682
00:25:37,745 --> 00:25:40,623
- One time he showed up,
he was pretty well lit up.

683
00:25:40,748 --> 00:25:43,334
I was like,
"My god, you can barely talk.

684
00:25:43,459 --> 00:25:44,418
Are you all right to go on?"

685
00:25:44,544 --> 00:25:46,587
I go,
"You shouldn't go on stage."

686
00:25:46,712 --> 00:25:49,423
Went on stage,
was crystal clear as a bell.

687
00:25:49,549 --> 00:25:51,259
Made everyone laugh, hilarious.

688
00:25:51,384 --> 00:25:52,635
Went back to the back stage,

689
00:25:52,760 --> 00:25:54,679
it was like,
[slurring] "Oh, my god."

690
00:25:54,804 --> 00:25:56,931
I'm like, "How the hell
did you just do that?"

691
00:25:57,056 --> 00:25:59,684
- But he did push it.
He did push it, as John did.

692
00:25:59,809 --> 00:26:03,020
He had automatic charisma
like John, you know.

693
00:26:03,145 --> 00:26:04,814
He was a light, you know.

694
00:26:04,981 --> 00:26:07,442
Heads would turn
when he came into the room.

695
00:26:07,567 --> 00:26:09,569
- Chris loved and idolized
Belushi,

696
00:26:09,694 --> 00:26:11,654
but he never imitated Belushi,

697
00:26:11,779 --> 00:26:12,779
in the same way

698
00:26:12,780 --> 00:26:14,991
that a Keith Richards
might emulate

699
00:26:15,116 --> 00:26:16,534
his old blues heroes

700
00:26:17,159 --> 00:26:19,579
but never really
sound like them.

701
00:26:19,704 --> 00:26:24,584
He took what he loved about them
and made it his own.

702
00:26:27,712 --> 00:26:30,381
- I got hired
for Saturday Night Live,

703
00:26:31,215 --> 00:26:32,675
and they said to me, you know,

704
00:26:32,800 --> 00:26:34,969
"Who do you think
is good there?"

705
00:26:35,094 --> 00:26:37,263
I listed a whole bunch of names,

706
00:26:37,722 --> 00:26:40,057
but the first name I said
was Chris Farley.

707
00:26:40,182 --> 00:26:42,268
- Come on.
It was undeniable.

708
00:26:43,227 --> 00:26:44,478
You couldn't stop Chris.

709
00:26:44,604 --> 00:26:47,773
He leaped over everyone,
and he should have.

710
00:26:48,024 --> 00:26:49,358
- Everybody recognized it

711
00:26:49,483 --> 00:26:51,902
even if they resented it
a little.

712
00:26:52,153 --> 00:26:53,654
You know, it was very clear.

713
00:26:53,779 --> 00:26:55,656
"Yeah, of course, you know."

714
00:26:55,781 --> 00:26:57,533
- All righty, everybody.

715
00:26:58,784 --> 00:27:00,536
- He was one of the people
we'd heard about,

716
00:27:00,661 --> 00:27:03,998
and you could tell
how much he loved to perform.

717
00:27:04,957 --> 00:27:08,294
This incredible sort of
generosity of spirit,

718
00:27:08,669 --> 00:27:11,088
and also just
a kind of innocence.

719
00:27:12,465 --> 00:27:14,508
I used to say
that he was the child

720
00:27:14,634 --> 00:27:17,470
that Dan Aykroyd
and John Belushi didn't have.

721
00:27:17,595 --> 00:27:20,264
There was just a joy
in what he was doing.

722
00:27:20,389 --> 00:27:21,599
You were always drawn to him.

723
00:27:21,724 --> 00:27:23,225
I knew I was bringing him
to New York.

724
00:27:23,351 --> 00:27:24,471
- It's a whale.
- It's a boy.

725
00:27:24,518 --> 00:27:25,728
- It's a whale boy.

726
00:27:25,853 --> 00:27:27,188
[applause]

727
00:27:32,818 --> 00:27:35,237
- It was a sad going-away,
a little bit.

728
00:27:35,363 --> 00:27:36,363
We were happy for him,

729
00:27:36,447 --> 00:27:37,531
but we were
also a little nervous...

730
00:27:37,657 --> 00:27:39,659
like, this poor little kid
from Madison

731
00:27:39,784 --> 00:27:43,537
going to go to New York City,
which he'd never been to,

732
00:27:43,663 --> 00:27:45,164
and be on a big TV show.

733
00:27:45,748 --> 00:27:48,000
It's kind of a lot for him,
and it was a lot for him.

734
00:27:48,125 --> 00:27:49,877
He was scared.

735
00:27:56,676 --> 00:27:59,095
- Five, four, three,
two, one, go.

736
00:27:59,637 --> 00:28:02,223
Live from New York,
it's Saturday Night!

737
00:28:02,348 --> 00:28:03,724
- Oh, one more thing.

738
00:28:03,849 --> 00:28:05,434
Live from New York,
it's Saturday Night!

739
00:28:05,559 --> 00:28:06,602
[audience cheers]

740
00:28:06,727 --> 00:28:09,689
- It's so intense
that it's a joke, you know.

741
00:28:09,814 --> 00:28:11,148
By the time you get off of it,

742
00:28:11,273 --> 00:28:13,192
you're like,
"How did I survive that?

743
00:28:13,317 --> 00:28:14,485
That's not possible."

744
00:28:14,610 --> 00:28:17,321
- There's nothing
like the live performance.

745
00:28:17,446 --> 00:28:20,449
It is the most exhilarating,
exciting...

746
00:28:20,825 --> 00:28:23,661
It's, like,
heart-pounding pressure.

747
00:28:24,453 --> 00:28:25,621
- You know, Dana Carvey says

748
00:28:25,746 --> 00:28:27,706
it's like being shot
out of a cannon without a net

749
00:28:27,707 --> 00:28:28,541
once a week.

750
00:28:28,666 --> 00:28:29,750
- "Chris Farley!"

751
00:28:29,875 --> 00:28:31,335
"Yeah, that's right.
Chris is here.

752
00:28:31,460 --> 00:28:33,741
We're going to see Chris Farley
